	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />An oil painting is created with the medium in mind. You use brush strokes, pigment streaks an even the height of the paint on the canvas to suggest depth of field. Several artists even left hairs from their brushes in the pigments to add texture.
<br />
<br />Likewise an NES game is created with it's medium in mind. Pixel locations are chosen to suggest detail that can't be represented (like Mario's mustache used to suggest a nose). Often times the dot crawl of the console and the interlacing of the TV set are also taken into account when creating graphics for the NES.
<br />
<br />I am with Koitsu on this one. Leave my graphics alone, please. If I wanted HD resolution for my games I'd go play XBox.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


